Question 1

getSymbols(c("BAC", "JPM"), src = "yahoo", from = "2020-01-01", to = "2024-12-31")
## [1] "BAC" "JPM"
BAC_logR <- diff(log(Ad(BAC)))
JPM_logR <- diff(log(Ad(JPM)))
logR <- na.omit(cbind(BAC = BAC_logR, JPM = JPM_logR))
u_data <- pobs(as.matrix(logR))

clayton.cop <- claytonCopula(dim = 2)
fit.clayton <- fitCopula(clayton.cop, u_data, method = "ml")
fit.clayton

grid <- expand.grid(U = u, V = v)

Question 2

u <- v <- seq(0.01, 0.99, length.out = 50)
grid <- expand.grid(U = u, V = v)
clayton_est <- claytonCopula(param = fit.clayton@estimate)
clayton_pdf <- matrix(dCopula(as.matrix(grid), clayton_est), nrow = 50)
contour(u, v, clayton_pdf,
        main = "Clayton Copula PDF with KDE Overlay",
        xlab = "U", ylab = "V")
kde_result <- kde2d(u_data[,1], u_data[,2], n = 50, lims = c(0,1,0,1))
contour(kde_result, add = TRUE, col = "blue", lty = 2)
legend("topright", legend = c("Clayton PDF", "Empirical KDE"),
       col = c("black", "blue"), lty = c(1, 2))

The plot compares the parametric density of the fitted Clayton copula, which are represented in the black lines with the non-parametric kernel density estimate represented in the blue dashed lines based on the BAC and JPM log returns. The Clayton copula shows the strongest connection between BAC and JPM when both are performing poorly. This is why the lines show the heavy dependence in the lower left corner. Meanwhile, the KDE is more flexible and show finer patterns in the data, especially in the middle and upper right parts. This shows that while the Clayton copula is good for some types of dependence like both stocks dropping, the KDE reveals more detailed patterns that the model might miss.

Question 3

X <- logR[, "BAC.Adjusted"]
Y <- logR[, "JPM.Adjusted"]
var_X <- var(X)
var_Y <- var(Y)
cov_XY <- cov(X, Y)

alpha_hat <- (var_Y - cov_XY) / (var_X + var_Y - 2 * cov_XY)
alpha_hat
##              JPM.Adjusted
## JPM.Adjusted    0.0748293
set.seed(123)
n <- nrow(logR)
B <- 1000
alpha_hats <- numeric(B)

for (i in 1:B) {
  idx <- sample(1:n, size = n, replace = TRUE)
  X_b <- X[idx]
  Y_b <- Y[idx]
  var_Xb <- var(X_b)
  var_Yb <- var(Y_b)
  cov_XYb <- cov(X_b, Y_b)
  alpha_hats[i] <- (var_Yb - cov_XYb) / (var_Xb + var_Yb - 2 * cov_XYb)
}
var_bootstrap <- var(alpha_hats)
var_bootstrap
## [1] 0.009677727
hist(alpha_hats, breaks = 30, col = "skyblue",
     main = "Bootstrap Distribution of Alpha Hat",
     xlab = expression(hat(alpha)), border = "white")
abline(v = alpha_hat, col = "red", lwd = 2, lty = 2)
legend("topright", legend = c("Original "), col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 2)

In this problem, we calculated the optimal value of alpha hat, which tells us how much weight to put on BAC compared to JPM in a portfolio to make the overall risk as small as possible. Using daily log-returns from adjusted close prices, we found that alpha hat = 0.07482952. This means putting about 7.5% of the investment in BAC and the remaining 92.5% in JPM would minimize daily fluctuations in portfolio returns. This approach is useful for conservative investors who want to reduce volatility.

To test how stable the alpha hat value is, we used bootstrap resampling to create 1000 alternative alpha hat estimates by randomly sampling with replacement from the original data. The histogram shows that most bootstrap values are centered around the original alpha hat, and the spread is relatively tight. This shows that our estimate is reliable and not heavily influenced by random chance. There is some variation, but the overall shape is roughly symmetric, and the original alpha hat, which is shown as a red dashed line, sits close to the middle. Overall, the bootstrap results give us confidence in the reliability of the original alpha hat estimate, and demonstrate how we can use resampling techniques to assess the stability of an optimal portfolio allocation.

The results compare three different autocorrelation functions (ACFs), which are the theoretical ACF of an ARMA(2,1) process, and two sample ACFs based on simulated data from parts 4a and 4b. The theoretical ACF, which is shown in dark red, is calculated using the AR and MA coefficients directly and represents what the ACF should look like in an ideal, infinite sample setting. We see a clear declining pattern, which reflects the memory of the time series over increasing lags. This is a reference model that we compare the sample plots to in order to assess how well the simulation captures the underlying process.

The sample ACFs from part 4a, in blue, and part 4b, in green, are based on finite samples of size 50. These include randomness and so they wont match the theoretical ACF exactly but we expect the general shape to be similar. Visually, both sample ACFs show the strongest correlations at lower lags and then gradually decrease, much like the theoretical ACF. However, because the samples are short, they also include noise, which can cause some spikes to appear more or less prominent. This variability is especially expected at higher lags. Overall, the similarity in early lag behavior shows that both simulations reflect the ARMA(2,1) structure fairly well, validating that our code and understanding of the process are accurate.

Question 4d

phi <- c(-0.5, 0.1)
theta <- 0.3
n <- 400

sim1 <- arima.sim(model = list(ar = phi, ma = theta), n = n)
sim2 <- arima.sim(model = list(ar = phi, ma = theta), n = n)
sim3 <- arima.sim(model = list(ar = phi, ma = theta), n = n)

par(mfrow = c(3, 1)) 
acf(sim1, main = "Sample ACF (SACF) for Simulation 1", col = "blue")
acf(sim2, main = "Sample ACF (SACF) for Simulation 2", col = "darkgreen")
acf(sim3, main = "Sample ACF (SACF) for Simulation 3", col = "purple")

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

The three SACF plots for the simulated ARMA(2,1) processes all show similar general patterns, especially at lower lags. Each plot has a strong autocorrelation at lag 1 followed by smaller positive and negative autocorrelations that gradually decline, which is consistent with the expected behavior of an ARMA(2,1) process. This general shape reflects the impact of the AR and MA terms used in the model. Since we used the same model parameters for all three simulations, the structure of the SACFs remains quite similar.

However, due to the randomness in the white noise generated internally by arima.sim, we can observe slight differences in the SACFs beyond the first few lags. These differences are especially noticeable at higher lags, where the autocorrelation values fluctuate around zero more randomly. This variation is expected when working with simulated data and highlights the importance of using larger sample sizes or averaging multiple runs to better estimate the true autocorrelation structure. Overall, all three SACFs are consistent with an ARMA(2,1) model and only differ slightly due to random variation in the generated data.
